<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=99568407812561></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f99568407812561><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=9&mid=99568407812561>RE: shamans rock</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=9&mid=99568407812561#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Jul 20th 10:54 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I'm 17th level now and I do 14 damage per hit with my hammer, with my buffs on. (a Cold iron morning star or northman mace would improve that) My 21st level tank (warrior) fellow does about 21 damage with his 2hS and just slightly slower than me. He Bashes and Kicks for more though. I'm a bit more decked out (equipment wise) than he is but thats because of wise investing. So while my damage isn't great I can keep up. Shamans can "melee", "Tank" indicates that "soaking" damage is your job. And it's true shamans don't soak damage well. Shamans can wear good armor compaired to all the int casters and druids, but really the only time you want a mob beating on you is if the mob -was- beating on a caster, cleric (who needs to be healing), or your tank is about to die and you are OOM. I take suprisingly little damage in full banded armor and buffed to high-heaven as long as the mob is blue or even, yellows and reds hurt bad though. The fact is that at low levels there are times you will want to melee. (Though if you ever end up the main tank you are in troubble, unless the rest are casters in a nuke group.)<br><br>Times where melee as a shaman may be nessisary or desired. (or at least not a terrible idea.)<br><br>1.) If the tanks don't seem to be taking much damage and the mob is under control. Jump in for some head bashing. It's fun and keeps your melee skills up. Just don't nuke then melee, because you don't want the agro.<br><br>2.) If the puller pulls a caster. Later in levels this may change, but at our level in perma everyone jumps on the caster. The attempt is to keep them from completing a cast. The nukers sit back and nuke though. Sence I am usualy the main healer in our group, and the only way I can do that without constantly being OOM is by use of "Inner Fire" I can't heal the tanks faster than the caster can nuke them, so we kill the casters fast and I heal the tanks after. (Been working well so far, just a few close calls.)<br><br>3.) If the tanks are focusing on the big baddies and a lesser one starts hitting a pure caster, pull it off of them. The little baddie will probably interupt your casting, but it's better than the pure caster dieing. However it should be the backup tanks (or rogue or monk) job to pull off of the casters. This is just if they have their hands too full.<br><br>4.) If you go OOM, sitting and medding (pre canabalise) is not a realy great option if things are going down the tubes. If there is one main baddie get in there and start whacking, if there are multiple smaller mobs hitting a badly wounded tank, see if you can get some of them to agro on you, and you can eather stand there and melee (in close quarters) or kite them for a while in the open.<br><br>The point is that Shamans are -just- good enough melee characters for it to be worthwhile to get in there and melee sometimes. As long as you don't have something else you should be doing.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
